</section>

<!-- TRUST BAR -->
<div class="trust-bar">
  <div class="trust-inner">
    <span class="trust-item">📋 BHGS Registration #A49573</span>
    <span class="trust-item">🔬 EPA-608 Refrigerant Certified</span>
    <span class="trust-item">🛡 Liability Insurance</span>
    <span class="trust-item">✅ Background-Checked Technicians</span>
    <span class="trust-item">⭐ BBB Accredited A+</span>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- INTRO + LICENSE VERIFICATION -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="intro-grid">
      <div class="intro-body">
        <p class="section-number">01 — Our Registration</p>
        <h2 class="section-title">In California, every appliance repair company must be registered with the state. Most aren't.</h2>

        <p>California Business and Professions Code requires any business that repairs household appliances for compensation to hold a valid registration with the Bureau of Household Goods and Services (BHGS) — a division of the California Department of Consumer Affairs. This covers refrigerators, washers, dryers, ovens, dishwashers, microwaves, and all major household appliances.</p>

        <p>This registration isn't a formality. It requires background verification, business registration documentation, and annual renewal. BHGS maintains jurisdiction to investigate complaints, impose fines, and revoke registrations. When you hire a registered company, you have a formal avenue for recourse if something goes wrong. When you hire an unregistered company, you don't.</p>

        <p>Our registration number is <strong>A49573</strong>. Look it up right now — it takes 30 seconds. Go to <strong>bhgs.dca.ca.gov</strong>, click License Lookup, and enter A49573. You'll see our business name, registration status, and expiration date. We encourage this. Companies that can't be verified this way shouldn't be handling your appliances.</p>

        <!-- LICENSE VERIFICATION BLOCK -->
        <div class="verify-block">
          <div class="v-label">✅ Verify Our Registration — Takes 30 Seconds</div>
          <h3>BHGS Registration #A49573 — Active</h3>
          <div class="license-badge">
            <div class="lb-number">A49573</div>
            <div class="lb-detail">
              <strong>Issuing Agency:</strong> California Bureau of Household Goods and Services (BHGS)<br>
              <strong>Department:</strong> Department of Consumer Affairs<br>
              <strong>Scope:</strong> Appliance Repair — Residential & Commercial<br>
              <strong>Renewal:</strong> Annual
            </div>
          </div>
          <a href="https://bhgs.dca.ca.gov/enforcement/lookup.shtml" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="verify-link">
            → Verify on California DCA Official Site
          </a>
        </div>
      </div>

      <aside class="sticky-cta">
        <div class="cta-label">Schedule Service</div>
        <a href={`tel:${phoneRaw}`} class="cta-phone">{phone}</a>
        <a href={`tel:${phoneRaw}`} class="btn-cta">Call Now — Same Day</a>
        <a href="/book" class="btn-cta" style="background:#222; margin-top:-4px;">Schedule Online</a>
        <div class="cta-sub">Mon–Sun 7am–9pm</div>
        <hr class="cta-divider" />
        <ul class="cta-detail">
          <li>BHGS Registration #A49573</li>
          <li>EPA-608 refrigerant certified</li>
          <li>Fully insured — liability + workers comp</li>
          <li>All techs background checked</li>
          <li>BBB Accredited A+ rating</li>
          <li>$89 diagnostic — waived with repair</li>
        </ul>
      </aside>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- BHGS vs CSLB -->
<section class="section section-black">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">02 — What the Registration Actually Means</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">BHGS registration vs. CSLB contractor license — two different things that often get confused</h2>
    <p class="lead">Many websites — including some appliance repair company pages — incorrectly describe their BHGS registration as a "CSLB license." These are two completely separate credentials from two separate California state agencies.</p>

    <div class="compare-grid">
      <div class="compare-card bhgs">
        <div class="cc-badge badge-bhgs">✅ What We Have</div>
        <h3>BHGS Registration — Bureau of Household Goods and Services</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Issued by CA Department of Consumer Affairs</li>
          <li>Specifically covers appliance repair businesses</li>
          <li>Mandatory for any company repairing household appliances for compensation</li>
          <li>Annual renewal required</li>
          <li>Subject to BHGS complaint and enforcement jurisdiction</li>
          <li>Verifiable at bhgs.dca.ca.gov</li>
          <li>Our number: <strong style="color:#70d070;">#A49573</strong></li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="compare-card cslb">
        <div class="cc-badge badge-cslb">ℹ️ Different Credential</div>
        <h3>CSLB License — Contractors State License Board</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Issued by the Contractors State License Board</li>
          <li>Covers construction and contracting work</li>
          <li>C-61/D-21 subcategory applies to certain appliance-related work</li>
          <li>Required for larger construction-type jobs exceeding $500</li>
          <li>Not the primary license required for appliance repair</li>
          <li>Verifiable at cslb.ca.gov</li>
          <li>Different agency, different scope</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p style="margin-top:20px; color:#666; font-size:0.9rem; line-height:1.7;">The bottom line: when you see an appliance repair company claim a "CSLB license for appliance repair" — ask them for the registration number and verify it on the BHGS lookup, not the CSLB lookup. The right credential for appliance repair in California is the BHGS registration. Ours is #A49573.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- RISKS OF UNREGISTERED COMPANIES -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">03 — Why Registration Matters for You</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Four concrete consequences of hiring an unregistered appliance repair company</h2>

    <div class="risks-grid">
      <div class="risk-card">
        <h3>No State Recourse If Something Goes Wrong</h3>
        <p>BHGS registered companies are subject to formal state oversight. If a registered company performs substandard work or causes damage, you can file a complaint with BHGS — which has enforcement authority including fines, license suspension, and revocation. An unregistered company has no standing with BHGS. Your only option is civil court.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="risk-card">
        <h3>Appliance Warranty May Be Voided</h3>
        <p>Many appliance manufacturers — including Samsung, LG, Whirlpool, and Sub-Zero — specify that warranty repairs must be performed by authorized or registered service companies. An unregistered technician's work can void your manufacturer's warranty on the repaired appliance and, in some cases, adjacent components. This matters most on newer appliances still under warranty.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="risk-card">
        <h3>Property Damage Goes Uncompensated</h3>
        <p>Registered appliance repair companies operating in California are required to carry liability insurance. If our technician damages your flooring, cabinetry, or the appliance itself during a repair, our insurance covers it. Unregistered technicians often operate without insurance. If they cause damage, you bear the cost — or pursue them personally, which is rarely worth the effort.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="risk-card">
        <h3>No Background Verification</h3>
        <p>BHGS registration includes business owner verification and background review. Our technicians additionally pass individual background checks before they ever enter a customer's home. Unregistered companies have no state-level verification requirement — there's no accountability for who they send to your home.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- APPLIANCE HAZARDS — compact version -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">04 — Why Proper Credentials Matter by Appliance Type</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Every major appliance category has specific technical hazards that require trained, registered technicians</h2>

    <div class="hazards-grid">
      <div class="hazard-card">
        <h3>🧊 Refrigerators & Freezers</h3>
        <div class="hazard-item">
          <div class="h-tag">Hazard</div>
          <p>Refrigerant (freon) leaks — toxic if inhaled, causes frostbite on contact, fire risk. Electrical shorts from damaged wiring.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="hazard-item">
          <div class="s-tag">Our Approach</div>
          <p>EPA-608 certified for refrigerant handling. Specialized leak detection equipment. Safe refrigerant recovery and recharge.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="hazard-card">
        <h3>🔥 Gas Ovens & Ranges</h3>
        <div class="hazard-item">
          <div class="h-tag">Hazard</div>
          <p>Gas leaks, carbon monoxide buildup, ignition failures that allow gas accumulation before ignition.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="hazard-item">
          <div class="s-tag">Our Approach</div>
          <p>Gas certified technicians. SoCalGas protocol followed for any gas smell. Pressure testing after any gas line work.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="hazard-card">
        <h3>👕 Washers & Dryers</h3>
        <div class="hazard-item">
          <div class="h-tag">Hazard</div>
          <p>Dryer lint buildup — leading cause of residential fires. Water leaks from washers cause mold, electrical shorts, and floor damage.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="hazard-item">
          <div class="s-tag">Our Approach</div>
          <p>Every dryer repair includes complementary dryer cleaning. Water line integrity checked on every washer repair.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="hazard-card">
        <h3>🍽️ Dishwashers</h3>
        <div class="hazard-item">
          <div class="h-tag">Hazard</div>
          <p>Water leaks leading to subfloor damage, mold growth under cabinetry, and electrical shorts from water intrusion.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="hazard-item">
          <div class="s-tag">Our Approach</div>
          <p>Full leak test and drain cycle verification after every dishwasher repair. Floor protection during service visit.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="hazard-card">
        <h3>⚡ Electric Ranges & Cooktops</h3>
        <div class="hazard-item">
          <div class="h-tag">Hazard</div>
          <p>240V electrical systems — significantly higher voltage than standard outlets. Wiring errors cause fire or electrocution.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="hazard-item">
          <div class="s-tag">Our Approach</div>
          <p>Circuit verified off before any component work. Proper torque on all electrical connections. Continuity test before power restoration.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="hazard-card">
        <h3>📡 Microwaves</h3>
        <div class="hazard-item">
          <div class="h-tag">Hazard</div>
          <p>High-voltage capacitors retain lethal charge even when unplugged. Door seal failure causes radiation leakage.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="hazard-item">
          <div class="s-tag">Our Approach</div>
          <p>Capacitor discharged before any internal access. Door seal integrity tested after every microwave repair.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
